    "                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    \n",

    "\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from matplotlib import rcParams"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rcParams[\"savefig.dpi\"] = 200\n",
    "rcParams[\"figure.dpi\"] = 200\n",
    "rcParams[\"font.size\"] = 20\n",
    "rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = [8, 5]\n",
    "rcParams[\"font.family\"] = \"sans-serif\"\n",
    "rcParams[\"font.sans-serif\"] = [\"Computer Modern Sans Serif\"]\n",
    "rcParams[\"text.usetex\"] = True"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Secondary Eclipse Spectroscopy  \n",
    "\n",
    "The `coronagraph` model can be used to model exoplanet observations using telescopes that don't even have a coronagraph. Here we will walk through a few examples of how to simulate secondary eclipse spectroscopy using the generic telescope noise modeling tools available with the `coronagraph` package. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0.1\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import coronagraph as cg\n",
    "print(cg.__version__)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Earth in Emission"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's start out by loading a model spectrum of the Earth:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lam, tdepth, fplan, fstar = cg.get_earth_trans_spectrum()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we'll define the telescope/instrument parameters for our simulation. Let's go big for this demo and use a 15 meter space telescope, with 50% throughput, and a mirror temperature at absolute zero so there is no thermal noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "telescope = cg.Telescope(Tput = 0.5,      # Throughput\n",
    "                         D = 15.,         # Diameter [m]\n",
    "                         R = 70,          # Resolving power (lam / dlam)\n",
    "                         lammin  = 5.0,   # Minimum Wavelength [um]\n",
    "                         lammax  = 20.0,  # Maximum Wavelength [um]\n",
    "                         Tsys = 0.0,      # Telescope mirror temperature [K]\n",
    "                        )  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We'll define the observed system as an Earth-Sun analog at 10 pc. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "planet = cg.Planet(a = 1.0,   # Semi-major axis [AU]\n",
    "                   d = 10.0,  # Distance [pc]\n",
    "                   Rp = 1.0   # Planet Radius [Earth Radii]\n",
    "                  )\n",
    "\n",
    "star = cg.Star(Rs = 1.0,      # Stellar Radius [Solar Radii]\n",
    "               Teff = 5700.   # Stellar Effective Temperature [K]\n",
    "              )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now let's specify the transit/eclipse duration `tdur` for the planet (Earth is this case), the number of eclipses to observe `ntran`, and the amount of observing out-of-eclipse (in units of eclipse durations) for each secondary eclipse observation `nout`. We're going to simulate the spectrum we would get after observing 1000 secondary eclipses of the Earth passing behind the Sun. Obviously this is ridiculous. One thousand secondary eclipses is not only a minimum of 8000 hours of observational time, but it would take 1000 years to aquire such a dataset! I promise that there is a lesson to be leared here, so let's push forward into infeasibility."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "tdur = 8.0 * 60 * 60  # Transit/Eclipse duration [seconds]\n",
    "ntran = 1e3           # Number of eclipses\n",
    "nout = 2.0            # Number of out-of-eclipse durations [transit durations]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we're ready to instantiate an `EclipseNoise` object for our simulation, which contains all of the information needed to perform the noise calculation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "en = cg.EclipseNoise(tdur = tdur,            # Transit Duration\n",
    "                     telescope = telescope,  # Telescope object\n",
    "                     planet = planet,        # Planet object\n",
    "                     star = star,            # Star object\n",
    "                     ntran = ntran,          # Number of eclipses to observe\n",
    "                     nout = nout)            # Number of out-of-eclipse observing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "At this point we are ready to run the simulation, so we simply call the `run_count_rates` method:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "en.run_count_rates(lam, fplan, fstar)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's now plot our fiducial secondary eclipse spectrum."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1745
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = en.plot_spectrum(SNR_threshold=0.0, Nsig=None)\n",
    "ax.text(15.0, 0.6, r\"CO$_2$\", va = \"center\", ha = \"center\");\n",
    "ax.text(9.6, 0.25, r\"O$_3$\", va = \"center\", ha = \"center\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can three key features. First, we note the general rising trend in the planet-to-star flux contrast with increasing wavelength. This occurs because, even though the Earth is much *much* more faint than the Sun at visible wavelengths, the blackbody intensity is weakly dependent on temperature in the Rayleigh-Jeans limit, so at these longer wavelengths the 288 K Earth and 5700 K Sun have more similar intensities. Second, we see absorption due to CO$_2$ at 15 µm. Finally, we see absorption due to O$_3$ at 9.6 µm. The rise in planet-to-star flux contrast with wavelength increases the relative size of absorption features in the emission spectrum. At first blush this would appear to make detecting molecules easier at longer wavelengths, however, photons are few and far between at these wavelengths and thermal noise tends to increase with wavelength, making the optimal wavelengths for molecular detection more complicated and telescope-dependent.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's take a look that the signal-to-noise as a function of wavelength. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1728
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = en.plot_SNRn()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sometimes it's nice to see the number of eclipses that must be observed to get a given S/N in each spectral element. Let's take a look at these devastating numbers for the Earth around the Sun. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1766
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = en.plot_ntran_to_wantsnr()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So this is really just too ridiculous. The ultimate reason for that can be gleaned from the last plot in this series, where we take a look at the photon count rates incident upon the detector from various noise sources compared to our signal.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1747
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = en.plot_count_rates()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that it's all about the star. The themral emission from the Sun outshines the thermal emission from the Earth by ~6 orders of magnitude at 20 µm, and there aren't enough photons to overcome this contrast in any reasonable amount of time. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simulating a *featureless* spectrum  \n",
    "\n",
    "We've heard a lot about featureless *transmission* spectra. This can occur due to high altitude aerosols or heavy and/or cool atmospheres. But what does a featureless emission spectrum look like?   \n",
    "\n",
    "In short, it looks like a ratio of blackbody fluxes:  \n",
    "\n",
    "$$ \\frac{F_p}{F_{\\star}} \\approx \\frac{B_p}{B_{\\star}} \\left ( \\frac{R_p}{R_{\\star}} \\right )^2 $$  \n",
    "\n",
    "But let's see how we can investigate this with the `coronagraph` model.  \n",
    "\n",
    "We're going to use the same planet and star as above, but now let's set a temperature for the planet:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "planet.Tplan = 288"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we can create a new `EclipseNoise` object for our featureless spectrum and calculate the photon count rates. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "enf = cg.EclipseNoise(tdur = tdur,\n",
    "                      telescope = telescope,\n",
    "                      planet = planet,\n",
    "                      star = star,\n",
    "                      ntran = ntran,\n",
    "                      nout = nout)\n",
    "\n",
    "enf.run_count_rates(lam)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's plot our new featureless spectrum and compare it with Earth's emission spectrum."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1745
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Plot Spectrum\n",
    "fig, ax = enf.plot_spectrum(SNR_threshold=0.0, Nsig=None, \n",
    "                            err_kws={'fmt': '.', 'c': 'C1', 'alpha': 1}, \n",
    "                            plot_kws={'lw': 1.0, 'c': 'C1', 'alpha': 0.5, 'label' : 'Featureless'})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add Earth's emission spectrum to the axis\n",
    "en.plot_spectrum(SNR_threshold=0.0, Nsig=None, ax0=ax, \n",
    "                 err_kws={'fmt': '.', 'c': 'C0', 'alpha': 1}, \n",
    "                 plot_kws={'lw': 1.0, 'c': 'C0', 'alpha': 0.5, 'label' : 'Earth'})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add legend\n",
    "leg = ax.legend(loc = 4)\n",
    "leg.get_frame().set_alpha(0.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Annotate molecules\n",
    "ax.text(15.0, 0.8, r\"CO$_2$\", va = \"center\", ha = \"center\");\n",
    "ax.text(9.6, 0.3, r\"O$_3$\", va = \"center\", ha = \"center\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## What about M-dwarfs?  \n",
    "\n",
    "So far we have looked at the extremely unrealistic scenario of observing Earth in secondary eclipse around the Sun. Now let's shift our focus to the late M-dwarf TRAPPIST-1 to see what the Earth would look like in secondary eclipse around this small, cool, dim star.  \n",
    "\n",
    "We'll start by modifying the effective temperature `Teff` and the radius `Rs` of the `star`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "star.Teff = 2510\n",
    "star.Rs = 0.117"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's instantiate an `EclipseNoise` object but now we'll use the transit duration of TRAPPIST-1e and only observe 25 secondary eclipses. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "enm = cg.EclipseNoise(tdur = 3432.0,\n",
    "                      telescope = telescope,\n",
    "                      planet = planet,\n",
    "                      star = star,\n",
    "                      ntran = 25.0,\n",
    "                      nout = nout)\n",
    "\n",
    "enm.run_count_rates(lam, fplan)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here's the emission spectrum:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1755
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = enm.plot_spectrum(SNR_threshold=0.0, Nsig=None)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we're in business!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1702
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = enm.plot_SNRn()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1408,
       "width": 1753
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "enm.recalc_wantsnr(wantsnr = 5.0)\n",
    "fig, ax = enm.plot_ntran_to_wantsnr()\n",
    "ax.set_yscale(\"linear\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylim(10,200);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that a S/N of 5 on each spectral element says nothing of the ability to detect molecules. The 15 µm CO$_2$ band as seen in the spectrum above is detected at greater than S/N=5 even though the S/N<5 *in each element* within the absorption band.   \n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, let's look at the photon count rates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1389,
       "width": 1777
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = enm.plot_count_rates()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now the contrast is  ${\\sim} 100 \\times$ more favorable than the Earth-Sun system. These systems are by no means easy to study, but they are something that we can work with!"
   ]
